\begin{abstract} We prove that the affine cone over a general primitively polarised K3 surface of genus $g$ is smoothable if and only if $g\le10$ or $g=12$. We discuss connections with the classification of Fano threefolds, and several examples of singularities with special behaviour.
\end{abstract}




\section{Introduction}

\subsection{} In 1974, Pinkham \cite{Pinkham} showed that the cone over a normal elliptic curve is smoothable if and only if the curve has degree $\le 9$. Schlessinger's 1973 criterion \cite{Schl} can be used to show that the cone over an abelian variety of dimension $\ge 2$ is never smoothable, and Mumford also used the same criterion to show that the cone over a curve of genus $\ge2$ embedded in sufficiently high degree is a non-smoothable singularity \cite{Mumford-rice}.

The cone over a K3 surface is a natural 3-dimensional generalisation of the cone over an elliptic curve, and our main result is the analogue of Pinkham's theorem.
\begin{thm}\label{thm!main} Let $S$ be a general K3 surface with primitive polarisation of genus $g$. Then the affine cone over $S$ is smoothable if and only if $g\le 10$ or $g=12$.
\end{thm}
We make more precise statements about what ``general" means in the article. This is connected with Brill--Noether loci as well as the rank of the Picard lattice.

